amshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"North Weston, Oxfordshire, England","Rotherfield, Sussex, England":"Rotherfield, Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Grey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish: variant of   Gray  .","German: dialect variant of   Grau  .","In some cases also an American shortened and altered form of Ukrainian <b>Grushko</b>: nickname or topographic name derived from a Russian-influenced transliteration of <i>grushka</i> ‘pear, pear tree’."],"variants":[{"name":"Gray","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish (especially Eastern Ulster; of Norman origin): habitational name from Graye in Calvados, France, named from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Graec(i)us</i>, meaning ‘Greek’ + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. This is probably the chief source of the surname in Britain.","English: nickname for someone with gray hair or a gray beard, from Middle English <i>grey</i> (Old English <i>grǣg</i>, <i>grēg</i>) ‘gray’. In Ireland it has been used as a translation of various Gaelic surnames derived from <i>riabhach</i> ‘brindled, gray’, including <b>Mac Giolla Riabhaigh</b>; see   McGreevy  . In North America, this surname has assimilated names with similar meaning from other languages.","French: habitational name from Gray in Haute-Saône or Le Gray in Seine-Maritime."]},{"name":"Greiwe","meanings":["German: possibly a nickname from Middle High German <i>greibe</i> ‘sharp, tangy, dour’. Compare   Grey  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":17,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":90,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Grey was born about 1365, in Rotherfield, Sussex, England as the daughter of Elizabeth de Poynings. She had at least 1 daughter with Richard Quartermain II."},"et":{"about 1365–":"umbes 1365–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1353–Male":"1353–Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1379–1421":"1379–1421","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1349–1368":"1349–1368","1349":"1349","1379":"1379","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","1353":"1353","about 1365":"umbes 1365","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","Willoughby, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"North Weston, Oxfordshire, England","Rotherfield, Sussex, England":"Rotherfield, Sussex, England"},"fi":{"about 1365–":"noin 1365–Kuollut","1365–Female":"1365–Kuollut","1353–Male":"1353–Kuollut","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1379–1421":"1379–1421","1375–Male":"1375–Kuollut","1349–1368":"1349–1368","1349":"1349","1379":"1379","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","1353":"1353","about 1365":"noin 1365","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","Willoughby, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"North Weston, Oxfordshire, England","Rotherfield, Sussex, England":"Rotherfield, Sussex, England"},"fr":{"about 1365–":"environ 1365–Décédée","1365–Female":"1365–Décédée","1353–Male":"1353–Décédé","1350–Male":"1350–Décédé","1379–1421":"1379–1421","1375–Male":"1375–Décédé","1349–1368":"1349–1368","1349":"1349","1379":"1379","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","1353":"1353","about 1365":"env